Lomnicki and others aim to remedy this one-sidedness by showing that the overall dynamical behavior of populations must ultimately be understood in terms of the behavior of individuals. Professor Lomnicki's wide-ranging presentation of this approach includes simple mathematical models aimed at describing both the origin and consequences of individual variation among plants and animals. The author contends that further progress in population ecology will require taking into account individual differences other than sex, age, and taxonomic affiliation--unequal access to resources, for instance. Population ecologists who adopt this viewpoint may discover new answers to classical questions of population ecology. Partly because it uses a variety of examples from many taxonomic groups, this work will appeal not only to population ecologists but to ecologists in general.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEcology. 0aPopulation biology. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Ecology.2bisacsh  aasymmetric competition.  acarrying capacity.  aclone.  acontinuous models.  adecision theory.  afish (territoriality).  afood used.  agroup selection.  aimmigration.  akin selection.  alife stages.  alogarithmic normal distribution.  amaintenance cost.  anormal distribution.  aoptimal decision theory.  apopulation extinction.  apresaturate emigration.  aquantal response, analysis of.  arank, individual.  arefraining from reproduction.  asatiation.  asocial hierarchy.  aterritoriality.  avariation coefficient.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691209616423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691209616.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-